<p>
  Almost everyone who sits down to write a speech makes the same mistake in the first draft: they
  write the way they think a speech is supposed to sound, instead of the way they actually talk.
  The result reads fine, but it doesn't sound like anyone in particular — which is exactly the
  problem.
</p>

<h2>Start by talking, not writing</h2>
<p>
  Before you write a single line, try saying it out loud instead. Talk through your story to a
  friend, into a voice memo, or just to an empty room. Notice the phrases you naturally reach for —
  the way you actually describe this person or this moment when no one's watching you write.
  Those phrases are almost always better than whatever you'd come up with staring at a blank page.
</p>
<p>
  This is also why our own writing process starts with listening rather than a blank prompt. The
  words people use when they're simply telling a story, unselfconsciously, are usually closer to
  their real voice than anything they'd draft from scratch.
</p>

<h2>Notice what you're imitating</h2>
<p>
  A lot of "speech voice" comes from imitation — movies, other weddings, greeting cards. Phrases
  like "words cannot express" or "since the day I met you, my life has never been the same" aren't
  wrong, exactly. They're just not <em>yours</em>. They belong to everyone, which means they belong
  to no one in particular.
</p>
<p>
  A simple test: if you can imagine a stranger saying the exact same line at a different wedding
  about a different person, it's probably borrowed rather than yours. The lines that are actually
  yours tend to be the ones only you could have written, because they include a detail only you
  would know.
</p>

<h2>Write it, then read it back to yourself</h2>
<p>
  After a first draft, read it aloud — not silently. Your ear catches what your eye misses. If a
  sentence makes you wince slightly, or feels like something you'd never actually say to this
  person's face, that's worth listening to. Trust that instinct over whatever sounded impressive on
  the page.
</p>
<blockquote>
  Our goal isn't to replace your voice. It's to help you discover it.
</blockquote>

<h2>Keep the imperfections that sound like you</h2>
<p>
  Polished isn't always the goal. A slightly informal turn of phrase, a small joke only your
  partner or your family would get, an unfinished thought that trails off because you got
  emotional — these are often the parts people remember, precisely because they don't sound
  written. Resist the urge to smooth every rough edge out of a speech that's supposed to sound like
  a person, not a press release.
</p>

<h2>If you're stuck, get a second pair of ears</h2>
<p>
  Sometimes you're too close to your own words to hear whether they sound like you. A second
  opinion — from a friend, or from someone trained to help without taking over — can be the
  difference between a speech that reads well and one that actually sounds like the person giving
  it. That's the entire idea behind our <a href="/services/">Review &amp; Refine service</a>: we
  don't rewrite your voice, we help you hear it more clearly.
</p>
